//! # 练习 9: `unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn` — R:
//! # Exercise 9: `unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn` — Unsafe Function Body Specification in Rust 2024 (Rust 1.95)
//!
//! **Difficulty**: Medium  
//! **Topic**: `unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn` lint, Rust 2024 behavior changes, unsafe block granularity control
//!
//! ## Background
//!
//! Before Rust 2021 and previous versions, the body of `unsafe fn` was considered an implicit `unsafe` block:
//! All unsafe operations within the function could be written directly without wrapping them in extra `unsafe {}`.
//!
//! This design had a problem: **It blurred the unsafe of the caller and the implementer.**  
//! `unsafe fn` marks "Unsafe permissions required to call this function",
//! but does not imply "All operations within this function's implementation automatically obtain unsafe permissions".
//!
//! Rust 2024 (enables `unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn` by default) changes this:  
//! The body of `unsafe fn` is **safe by default**, internal unsafe operations still need to be explicitly wrapped in `unsafe {}` blocks.
//! This makes the boundary of unsafe clearer, making every line of unsafe code explicitly visible.
//!
//! ## Requirements
//!
//! - Understand the difference between `unsafe fn` (calling constraint) and `unsafe {}` (permission grant)
//! - Refactor Rust 2021-style `unsafe fn` to Rust 2024-style
//! - Use minimally granular `unsafe {}` blocks inside unsafe fn body
//! ```

